countries protect their own firms from world market exposure during international trade, but why? Governments may protect their firms from world market exposure during international trade for a number of reasons. One reason may be to ensure that the country's firms remain competitive in the global marketplace. Additionally, governments may want to ensure that their firms are able to sell their products and services in foreign markets. By protecting their firms from world market exposure, governments can help their firms become more successful in the global economy.
